{
  "texts": [
    "11 The other approach that Buckner (2024) classifies as \"empiricist\" takes a more developmentalist perspective.",
    "Proponents of this view hold that human infants lack the means necessary to think of themselves as separate beings due to being dependent on a caregiver.",
    "Instead, social cognition arises due to the influence of affective states (such as sympathy) early in life, which help to form and shape the child's social cognition over time.",
    "In AI, this approach materialises as the field of affective computing (Picard, 2000), where we aim to enable AI to recognise the same kind of cues that allow humans to be sensitive to the mental states of other agents.",
    "An intriguing possibility that is suggested by Buckner (2024) is that the current RLHF method could be further improved and extended if we \"find ways to leverage a wider range of qualitatively distinct valences of human feedback\" (Buckner, 2024, p. 341) like these affective states-either of these aforementioned approaches present possibilities for improving upon ToM capabilities of current systems."
  ]
}